    #Function to plot business summary of top n parent institutions for a particular year:
    def plotParentSummaryyear(masterdata, year, top):
    
        #Summarising the master data
        summary = parentSummary(masterdata)
        summary = summary.sort(['year', 'state', 'prcnttotalamountlent'], ascending = [1,1,0])
        summary = summary.groupby(['year', 'state']).head(top)
        summary.reset_index(inplace = True)
        
        #filtering for the concerned year    
        df = summary[summary.year == year]
        
        #adjusting the units and passing columns as plot attributes such as size and brightness of the scatter
        df.noofloans = df.noofloans/1000
        df.alphas = 0.85*df.noofloans/max(df.noofloans)
        df.sizes =  0.1*df.medianloanamount
         
        #Datasource for the bokeh glyph
        source = ColumnDataSource(data = dict(
            x = list(df.state),
            y = list(df.prcnttotalamountlent),
            sizes = list(df.sizes),
            alphas = list(df.alphas),
            noofloans = list(df.noofloans),
            parent = list(df.parent_Institution),
            medianloanamount = list(df.medianloanamount),))
            
        #Hover tool for tooltip  
        hover = HoverTool(tooltips=[("Institution:", "@parent"),
                                        ("Marketshare: ", "@y"),
                                        ("Median_loan_amount (in USD 1000s): ", "@medianloanamount"),
                                        ("Noofloans (in 1000s):", "@noofloans"),
                                        ])
            
        hover.point_policy = "follow_mouse"
        
        #Declaring figure dimensions, title, xlabel, ylabel etc.,
        p = figure(title='Market Share of top Institutions',
               x_range=list(set(df.state)), x_axis_label = "State", y_axis_label = "Percentage of amount lent in that state",
               tools = [hover], plot_height = 300, plot_width = 800)
        #Circular glyph    
        r = p.circle(y = 'y', x = 'x', size = 'sizes', color = 'saddlebrown', alpha = 'alphas', source = source)
            
        return p,r
    
    
    #Function for plotting county heatmap showing distribution of various parameters across the

    def countymap(column, year):
     
        #importing latitude, longitude and names of counties and states under consideration
        state_xs = [states[code]["lons"] for code in states if code in ['DC','DE','MD', 'VA', 'WV']]
        state_ys = [states[code]["lats"] for code in states if code in ['DC','DE','MD', 'VA', 'WV']]
        county_xs=[counties[code]["lons"] for code in counties if counties[code]["state"] in ['dc','de','md', 'va', 'wv']]
        county_ys=[counties[code]["lats"] for code in counties if counties[code]["state"] in ['dc','de','md', 'va', 'wv']]
    
        #Converting all names to lower to match with the names in our home loans data
        for code in counties:
            counties[code]["name"] = counties[code]["name"].lower()
    
        county_name = [counties[code]["name"] for code in counties if counties[code]["state"] in ['dc','de','md', 'va', 'wv']]
        state_name = [counties[code]["state"] for code in counties if counties[code]["state"] in ['dc','de','md', 'va', 'wv']]
        
        #Getting values of variable under consideration:
        rate = mapsummary(column, year)
    
        palette.reverse()
        #Passing data source to glypgh
        source = ColumnDataSource(data=dict(
        x=county_xs,
        y=county_ys,
        name=county_name,
        sname = state_name,
        rate=rate,))
    
        #Tooltip declaration
        hover = HoverTool(tooltips = [
        ("County: ", "@name"),
        ("State: ", "@sname"),
        ("variable: ","@rate"),])
        hover.point_policy = "follow_mouse"
        
        #Declaring figure details
        p = figure(
        title="County Map", plot_width = 800, plot_height = 500,
        x_axis_location=None, y_axis_location=None, tools = [hover])
        
        #No grid as we are plotting on a map
        p.grid.grid_line_color = None
         
        #Color coding the variable under consideration
        color_mapper = LogColorMapper(palette=palette)
         
        #Patches glyph to draw counties using boundries defined by the list of latitudes and longitudes for each county    
        r = p.patches('x', 'y', source=source,
              fill_color={'field': 'rate', 'transform': color_mapper},
              fill_alpha=0.7, line_color="white", line_width=0.5)
        
        return p,r

Introduction:

::

    The following analysis is carried out on the home loan data published by Federal Financial Institutions Examination Council. This data consists of two data sets:

    1) "2012_to_2014_loans_data":
            This data set contains information about the home loans as reported by the lending institution to the reporting agency for the years 2012 to 2014 within the states where "Change Financial" operates. The data describes various characteristics of the home loan such as loan type, loan purpose, loan amount, applicant income, state, county, government coverage (if any) etc., This data has been filtered to contain only 1-4 family, owner-occupied home loans with an "originated" action type and that were secured by a first or subordinate lien. Description of few important variables of the dataset are as follows:
            
       * MSA_MD_Description - Description of MSA/MD (Metropolitan Statistical Area (MSA)/Metropolitan Division (MD)
       * FFIEC_Median_Family_Income - Median family income for the MSA/MD in which the census tract is located
       * Number_of_Owner_Occupied_Units - Number of units, in the census tract in which the owner lives
       * Conforming_Limit_000 - Single Unit Conforming Loan limit for the given county
       * Loan_Type_Description - Specifies whether the loan was "conventional," i.e., not backed by a government
       * Applicant_Income_000 - The total income used for decisioning the loan
       * Lien_Status_Description -  If first lien position - least risk. Subordinate liens carry more risk


    2) "2012_to_2014_Institutions_data":
            This data set contains the information about the lending institutions such as the state, county and     parent corporation etc.,

Conforming\_Status(corresponding to county),
Tract\_to\_MSA\_MD\_Income\_Pct and MSA\_MD\_Description. We will try to
find a fix for these null values later. Applicant\_Income, Loan\_Amount
and Median\_Family\_Income are some of the impotant numerical variables
as they represent the state of home loan market, let us inspect those
variables.

Institutions Data: There are missing values in Parent\_Name\_TS,
Parent\_State\_TS, Parent\_Zip\_Code which we will not deal with for the
sake of our analysis. We will try to explore whether there is any way to
impute PArent\_Name\_TS, if necessary.

    # Convert median_income to  integer and replace missing values with median of median_income:
    median_income = list(loan.FFIEC_Median_Family_Income)
    median_income = [np.rint(str_to_int(i, -99999999999)/1000) for i in median_income]

Median\_Family\_Income is coded as string in units of USD1000. These
values are converted to integer format. There are only 1677

will impute them with median value of median\_income.

-  Variable "Applicant\_Income\_000" is coded as string and there are
   117853 missing values coded in the string form as 'NA '
-  Majority of the missing values are from the data reported to agencies
   7 and 9 and from the years 2012 and 2013
-  We can either remove these observations while considering applicant
   income in our analysis or use median family income to replace these
   missing values
-  As the missing values make up significant portion of the data, it is
   better to replace them with median family income

.. code:: python

    # Converting applicant income to integer format while replacing missing values with median_family_income in that MSA/MD
    
    income = list(loan.Applicant_Income_000)
    median_income = list(loan.FFIEC_Median_Family_Income)
    
    income = [str_to_int(income[i], median_income[i]) for i in range(len(income))]
    loan.Applicant_Income_000 = income
    
    del income
    del median_income

Exploratory Analysis:
---------------------

Our data corresponds to five states- 1) West Virginia, 2) Virginia, 3)
District of Columbia, 4) Maryland and 4) Delaware for the years of 2012,
2013 and 2014. Let us have a glimpse of the demographics such as
applicant income, loan amount and number of home loans etc., For the
purpose of our analysis, we will use median applicant income and median
loan amount, as there are significantly extreme outliers in our data
(though capped).

-  Median Income is not the median income of that MSA/ MD.

Median Income and Amount lent :
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

::

    From the above plots it is apparent that median applicant income and median loan amount are highly correlated with eachother as they follow the same trend across the states over the years. This is because both the fields are conseqences of the cost of living of that particular region. There is no significant change in median applicant income and median amount lent in all the states with time (period under consideration is very short). District of Columbia has the highest median income and amount lent followed by Maryland, Virginia, Delaware and West Virginia in that order.

Number of Loans:
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

::

    Above plot shows the distribution of number of loans lent across the states. There is a significant drop in the number of loans across all the states. Virginia has most number of home loans followed by Maryland, West Virginia, Delaware and District of Columbia in that order. Although DC has highest median amount lent, number of loans is significantly lower. Maryland does better interms of both median loan amount and number of loans.

Market share(Percentage of total amount lent):
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

-  Size of the circle represents median loan amount
-  Transperancy of the circle represents median applicant income
-  Please hover the cursor over the blobs to view other characteristics

The distribution of market share of the states does not vary much. As
noticed earlier median income (transperancy) and median loan amount
(size) are directly proportional. Virinia (around 50%) and Maryland
(around 35%) contribute majorly to the market of home loans followed by
District of Columbia, Delaware and West Virginia in that order.

Loan type (Coneventional Vs Government Assured) Summary:
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

-  There is no significant change in the distribution of conventional
   and non-conventional loan types in terms of total amount lent through
   2012 to 2014. Majority of the market share is of conventional loans
   (around 70%)

-  Each of the state's market except for DC, has around 70% contribution
   from convntional loans. Around 85% of DC's home loan aket is
   comprised of conventional loans

Loan Purpose (Purchase or Refinance):
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

-  There is a drastic shift in the home loan market during 2012 to 2014
   in terms of the distribution of purchase and refinance loans.
   Refinance loans are on decline (their share plumetted from around 73%
   to 40%)
-  There is no glaring difference in Purchase-Refinance loan
   distribution among different states.

-  From the above plot of Number of loans Vs Years, it can be noticed
   that while there is not much change in the number of purchase
   category loans, refinance loans declined from around 400k in 2012 to
   around 120k in 2014
-  Home loan business i.e., in terms of total amount lent has not
   changed for purchase loans, but that of refinance loans has plumetted
-  Decline in business can be attributed to decline in refinance loans

    <p><code>&lt;Bokeh Notebook handle for <strong>In[37]</strong>&gt;</code></p>



-  Please use the inetractor tool to select year and the variable of
   interest
-  Above heat map shows the distribution of various parameters such as
   total amount lent, number of loans, median loan amount etc.,
-  Please hover the county to find its details such as county name,
   state and the vale of the variable selected

Summary:
~~~~~~~~

-  Missing values of median\_income\_in\_MSA/MD are populated using the
   median of the median\_income\_in\_MSA/MD
-  Missing values of applicant\_income are populated using
   median\_income\_in\_MSA/MD (There are 117853 missing values and
   majority of them are reported to agency 9, it is better to have a
   look at the data source)
-  No missing values of loan amount observed
-  There are missing values in some other variables such as
   county\_name, conformin limit etc., but they are ignored for the
   purpose of this analysis
-  Applicant income, median income are coded as strings in the given
   dataset
-  All the monetary variables are expressed in units of USD1000 for te
   purpose of analysis

-  Though there are very few outliers in the variables, applicant income
   and loan amount, they are so extreme which makes their authenticity
   questionable. These variales are capped at 99th percentile (which
   seemed a reasonable value i.e., closer to the median value)

-  There are 519 unique parent institutions operating in the states
   under consideration through their sunbsidaries

-  Median Loan Amount is positvely correlated with median applicant
   income, which can be attributed to the cost of living in a particular
   area. Median income and medina oan amount are almost constant with
   time across diffrent states

-  There is a significant drop in the number of loans across all the
   states. Virginia has most number of home loans followed by Maryland,
   West Virginia, Delaware and District of Columbia in that order.
   Although DC has highest median amount lent, number of loans is
   significantly lower. Maryland does better interms of both median loan
   amount and number of loans

-  There is a decrease in home loan business (total amount lent) of 17%
   from 2012 to 2013 and 35% from 2013 to 2014

-  The distribution of market share of the states does not vary much.
   Virinia (around 50%) and Maryland (around 35%) contribute majorly to
   the market of home loans

-  Majority of the market share is of conventional loans (around 70%)
   (non government assured)

-  Refinance loans are on decline (their share plumetted from around 73%
   to 40%. Distriution of refinance vs purchase is similar among all the
   states

-  While there is not much change in the number of purchase category
   loans, number of refinance loans decresed from around 400k in 2012 to
   around 120k in 2014. Decline in home loan market is majorly due to
   decline in refinance loan market

-  It is better to gain insight into why there is a decline in refinance
   loan and that might provide a possible business opportunity

-  Potential counties for business can be maped from the above heat map
   showing the distribution of various charactersitics of home loan
   market
